00:42:06.910 --> 00:42:09.280
And she asks, how can
parents lay the groundwork

00:42:09.280 --> 00:42:10.832
for these skills in
younger children?

00:42:10.832 --> 00:42:13.040
RACHEL SIMMONS: I'm so happy
you asked that, Hillary,

00:42:13.040 --> 00:42:15.350
because I'm also the
parent of a younger child.

00:42:15.350 --> 00:42:18.070
And you may know the
common phrase, little kids,

00:42:18.070 --> 00:42:20.050
little problems, big
kids, big problems.

00:42:20.050 --> 00:42:24.040
And so by that, I take from that
little kids are so much more

00:42:24.040 --> 00:42:26.450
impressionable and a little
bit easier to work with.

00:42:26.450 --> 00:42:30.070
So what are some things you
can do with a young child?

00:42:30.070 --> 00:42:33.130
One, you can make the
practice of gratitude part

00:42:33.130 --> 00:42:34.620
of every breakfast.

00:42:34.620 --> 00:42:38.570
So every day breakfast, what is
one thing you're grateful for?

00:42:38.570 --> 00:42:41.064
And you say it, and they say it.

00:42:41.064 --> 00:42:42.730
Again, one of the
benefits of doing this

00:42:42.730 --> 00:42:45.310
with younger children
is that, as they proceed

00:42:45.310 --> 00:42:47.170
into the eye-rolling
years, they at least

00:42:47.170 --> 00:42:51.100
have this groundwork
that's been laid,

00:42:51.100 --> 00:42:53.500
which helps keep them
much more connected.

00:42:53.500 --> 00:42:55.870
You have a much better
chance of hanging on.

00:42:55.870 --> 00:42:59.770
Another thing you can
do is talk with them

00:42:59.770 --> 00:43:02.080
about the way they
talk to themselves.

00:43:02.080 --> 00:43:05.950
So if you're physically
comfortable going to a place

00:43:05.950 --> 00:43:09.010
where you could maybe jump
over something with your child,

00:43:09.010 --> 00:43:11.440
like, for example,
bouldering, climbing on rocks,

00:43:11.440 --> 00:43:13.540
or walking by a
creek and stepping

00:43:13.540 --> 00:43:15.400
on the rocks in
the creek, and you

00:43:15.400 --> 00:43:17.380
sense your daughter
anxious about something--

00:43:17.380 --> 00:43:19.000
and I'm using the
creek as an example,

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:20.020
but there are all
kinds of things

00:43:20.020 --> 00:43:22.330
we might do with our child
where she feels afraid

00:43:22.330 --> 00:43:23.470
when she's young.

00:43:23.470 --> 00:43:25.720
You say to her,
it's a good thing

00:43:25.720 --> 00:43:28.030
to talk to yourself in
a positive way, to say,

00:43:28.030 --> 00:43:29.180
I can do this.

00:43:29.180 --> 00:43:29.840
I can do this.

00:43:29.840 --> 00:43:32.620
Teach her what internal
self-talk sounds like.

00:43:32.620 --> 00:43:35.170
This is certainly something
my daughter has absolutely

00:43:35.170 --> 00:43:37.480
internalized, and who
is almost six years old,

00:43:37.480 --> 00:43:39.580
and who does this frequently.

00:43:39.580 --> 00:43:42.550
Another great thing to do is
when your daughter is working

00:43:42.550 --> 00:43:45.010
on something that's
challenging for her,

00:43:45.010 --> 00:43:47.680
and you can feel her starting
to either get frustrated or want

00:43:47.680 --> 00:43:49.330
to walk away from
it, you go up and you

00:43:49.330 --> 00:43:51.610
give her tons of praise,
and you say, look

00:43:51.610 --> 00:43:53.440
how far you've gotten at this.

00:43:53.440 --> 00:43:55.930
Look how much
you've done already.

00:43:55.930 --> 00:43:57.970
And that's known
as process praise.

00:43:57.970 --> 00:44:01.810
Process praise is about
making sure kids feel really

00:44:01.810 --> 00:44:04.240
good about being in the
middle of a challenging

00:44:04.240 --> 00:44:07.630
process, making sure they feel
praised for sticking with it

00:44:07.630 --> 00:44:10.390
and being a part of it,
as opposed to waiting

00:44:10.390 --> 00:44:13.900
until they've finished and cross
the finish line, as it were,

00:44:13.900 --> 00:44:15.110
to give them the praise.

00:44:15.110 --> 00:44:16.930
We know from research that--

00:44:16.930 --> 00:44:18.520
and I find this
amazing that they've

00:44:18.520 --> 00:44:21.370
been able to figure this
out, coming out of Stanford--

00:44:21.370 --> 00:44:24.550
that even in toddlerhood,
boys get more process

00:44:24.550 --> 00:44:26.200
praise than girls.

00:44:26.200 --> 00:44:27.760
Which is unbelievable to me.

00:44:27.760 --> 00:44:31.880
And if you hear process praise,
if you are praised for--

00:44:31.880 --> 00:44:33.940
another way to ask
this is, let's say

00:44:33.940 --> 00:44:35.560
your kid is working
on something,

00:44:35.560 --> 00:44:38.242
and you say, tell me about
the strategy that you used.

00:44:38.242 --> 00:44:39.700
And by the way,
teach them the word

00:44:39.700 --> 00:44:42.520
"strategy," because strategy
implies there's always

00:44:42.520 --> 00:44:43.600
more than one solution.

00:44:43.600 --> 00:44:45.590
There's lots of different
ways to do something.

00:44:45.590 --> 00:44:48.970
So what kind of strategy did
you use to figure that out?

00:44:48.970 --> 00:44:51.940
And they can get excited about
what they've done so far.

00:44:51.940 --> 00:44:54.610
So all of this helps
make kids braver

00:44:54.610 --> 00:44:57.250
because it means they don't
have to perform at the highest

00:44:57.250 --> 00:44:58.010
level.

00:44:58.010 --> 00:45:00.250
It means they know
you care when they're

00:45:00.250 --> 00:45:01.900
in it and in the
process and trying.

00:45:01.900 --> 00:45:04.720
So those are all
things that you can do.

00:45:04.720 --> 00:45:06.860
There's so much to do
with younger girls.

