my mother and I

00:45:26.970 --> 00:45:29.020
have been talking about
and trying to work out

00:45:29.020 --> 00:45:32.800
for a long time is the
fact that it didn't so much

00:45:32.800 --> 00:45:34.420
matter to me what she said.

00:45:34.420 --> 00:45:36.160
It mattered to me what she did.

00:45:36.160 --> 00:45:38.200
And I would just
mirror her behaviors,

00:45:38.200 --> 00:45:40.630
even if she was telling
me the opposite.

00:45:40.630 --> 00:45:45.040
And as somebody who struggles
with things in my own life,

00:45:45.040 --> 00:45:46.810
I wonder if you have
any advice on if you

00:45:46.810 --> 00:45:50.680
know you have a problem, and you
participate in a behavior that

00:45:50.680 --> 00:45:53.980
would be very damaging to mimic,
and yet you're still struggling

00:45:53.980 --> 00:45:55.930
yourself to not
do it, how do you

00:45:55.930 --> 00:45:59.050
communicate this with somebody
who might be watching you

00:45:59.050 --> 00:46:00.794
as a role model?

00:46:00.794 --> 00:46:02.460
RACHEL SIMMONS: That's
a great question.

00:46:02.460 --> 00:46:04.630
So meaning you have
awareness of the behavior

00:46:04.630 --> 00:46:06.160
that someone is mimicking.

00:46:06.160 --> 00:46:10.300
Well, of course, the pat answer
is do as I say but not as I do.

00:46:10.300 --> 00:46:13.095
But I think you're pointing
to something deeper,

00:46:13.095 --> 00:46:14.530
and something
that's been studied,

00:46:14.530 --> 00:46:16.580
actually-- it's just
beginning to be studied,

00:46:16.580 --> 00:46:18.700
which is the way that
young people can tell

00:46:18.700 --> 00:46:21.700
the difference between what
their parents' values are

00:46:21.700 --> 00:46:23.380
and what their
parents actually say.

00:46:23.380 --> 00:46:25.960
So in other words, teens
have a great BS detector.

00:46:25.960 --> 00:46:27.980
They know that their
parent might say,

00:46:27.980 --> 00:46:29.456
oh, I really want
you to be happy.

00:46:29.456 --> 00:46:31.330
And they, at the same
time, know their parent

00:46:31.330 --> 00:46:33.070
is very committed
to them getting

00:46:33.070 --> 00:46:35.830
into the best possible
college, which may actually

00:46:35.830 --> 00:46:37.810
contraindicate their happiness.

00:46:37.810 --> 00:46:40.030
And so I think
that you're really

00:46:40.030 --> 00:46:43.110
highlighting something that's
quite new in the research.

00:46:43.110 --> 00:46:44.860
But, of course, your
question is about how

00:46:44.860 --> 00:46:48.940
do you relate to somebody when
you know that you're modeling

00:46:48.940 --> 00:46:51.470
something that's not healthy.

00:46:51.470 --> 00:46:54.010
And I guess I
think the kind of--

00:46:54.010 --> 00:46:56.170
I know Brené Brown was
here at Google yesterday.

00:46:56.170 --> 00:46:58.900
I think vulnerability--
authentic vulnerability--

00:46:58.900 --> 00:47:00.020
is really important.

00:47:00.020 --> 00:47:04.450
So to be able to say almost
as part admission of what's

00:47:04.450 --> 00:47:06.730
going on but also
part apology, if you

00:47:06.730 --> 00:47:08.170
believe it is called for.

00:47:08.170 --> 00:47:11.620
I know on a smaller scale
that in the moments where

00:47:11.620 --> 00:47:15.230
I let my own child down,
when I fail my own child,

00:47:15.230 --> 00:47:17.950
whether it's because I have
yelled in a way that wasn't

00:47:17.950 --> 00:47:21.400
appropriate or called for,
or I have been too dismissive

00:47:21.400 --> 00:47:23.890
or distracted, I catch
myself, and I say,

00:47:23.890 --> 00:47:26.416
I'm really sorry
for what I just did.

00:47:26.416 --> 00:47:27.790
And she'll say,
it's OK, it's OK.

00:47:27.790 --> 00:47:30.040
I think she gets like, Mom,
please stop being awkward,

00:47:30.040 --> 00:47:33.850
because we live in New
England, and she apparently

00:47:33.850 --> 00:47:35.710
has no feelings.

00:47:35.710 --> 00:47:38.370
Anyway, she's like,
please stop, please stop.

00:47:38.370 --> 00:47:42.469
And she's only six, but I try to
say to her, this wasn't right,

00:47:42.469 --> 00:47:43.510
and I need to make right.

00:47:43.510 --> 00:47:45.593
I need to meet it right,
I need to make it better.

00:47:45.593 --> 00:47:46.660
I don't beat myself up.

00:47:46.660 --> 00:47:48.670
So it's a combination
of that vulnerability--

00:47:48.670 --> 00:47:50.680
that authentic vulnerability--

00:47:50.680 --> 00:47:54.520
but also being willing to
be accountable, and to say,

00:47:54.520 --> 00:47:55.926
I don't have it all together.

00:47:55.926 --> 00:47:57.550
And it goes back to
what I said earlier

00:47:57.550 --> 00:48:00.820
about the importance of making
mistakes in front of your kids,

00:48:00.820 --> 00:48:04.300
because your kids need to know
how to screw up as much as they

00:48:04.300 --> 00:48:06.670
need to know how to succeed.

00:48:06.670 --> 00:48:09.520
You can't know how
to succeed truly

00:48:09.520 --> 00:48:11.980
well if you don't have the
tools to make mistakes.

00:48:11.980 --> 00:48:14.150
And yet so many
of us as parents,

00:48:14.150 --> 00:48:15.790
we err too much on
the side of we're

00:48:15.790 --> 00:48:17.390
going teach how to succeed.

00:48:17.390 --> 00:48:19.960
And that's really part of
what this book is about.

00:48:19.960 --> 00:48:22.240
I'm a big fan of
the book "Lean In."

00:48:22.240 --> 00:48:23.830
And I believe what
we need to teach

00:48:23.830 --> 00:48:27.160
our kids to do is to lean
inside so that they have

00:48:27.160 --> 00:48:30.250
the tools to be
strong and to navigate

00:48:30.250 --> 00:48:33.550
the barriers and the
unforeseen moments that arise

00:48:33.550 --> 00:48:37.015
when they are pursuing success.

00:48:37.015 --> 00:48:37.890
TRUDI MCCANNA: Great.

00:48:37.890 --> 00:48:38.930
We have another
question on the Dory.

00:48:38.930 --> 00:48:40.100
This one's from Elizabeth.

00:48:40.100 --> 00:48:43.310
She says she's currently reading
"The Curse of the Good Girl,"

00:48:43.310 --> 00:48:46.430
published in 2010, specifically
in regard to part two,

00:48:46.430 --> 00:48:47.750
Breaking the Curse.

00:48:47.750 --> 00:48:49.970
Is there anything
you'd update or advice

00:48:49.970 --> 00:48:53.210
you'd modify based on things
you've learned and observed

00:48:53.210 --> 00:48:54.470
since it was published?

00:48:54.470 --> 00:48:57.950
RACHEL SIMMONS: Wow, that's
a really good question.

00:48:57.950 --> 00:49:01.220
Well, I guess yes, absolutely.

00:49:01.220 --> 00:49:03.560
And I actually talk about
this in "Enough As She Is."

00:49:03.560 --> 00:49:05.360
That's a wonderful question.

00:49:05.360 --> 00:49:07.267
Yeah, I kind of realized
that I screwed up

00:49:07.267 --> 00:49:09.725
a little bit in "The Curse of
the Good Girl." so Elizabeth,

00:49:09.725 --> 00:49:10.466
mea culpa.

00:49:10.466 --> 00:49:12.090
And if you decide
that you like my work

00:49:12.090 --> 00:49:13.909
enough to read the
next one, you'll

00:49:13.909 --> 00:49:15.200
see I actually talk about this.

00:49:15.200 --> 00:49:16.658
So in "The Curse
of the Good Girl,"

00:49:16.658 --> 00:49:20.180
I argue that the most important
thing girls need in order

00:49:20.180 --> 00:49:22.220
to thrive is to
break that curse,

00:49:22.220 --> 00:49:25.040
is to not have to sit
like a girl all the time,

00:49:25.040 --> 00:49:28.310
is to be able to speak
up and not feel like they

00:49:28.310 --> 00:49:30.320
have to be modest
and have conflicts,

00:49:30.320 --> 00:49:32.150
and express their feelings.

00:49:32.150 --> 00:49:34.430
And I thought that if
girls could do that,

00:49:34.430 --> 00:49:39.950
they would lead happier,
healthier lives.

00:49:39.950 --> 00:49:41.540
So here's the
problem with that, is

00:49:41.540 --> 00:49:43.340
that I was putting
way too much emphasis

00:49:43.340 --> 00:49:44.840
on the role of the girl.

00:49:44.840 --> 00:49:48.260
I was not at all thinking
about how toxic the culture is

00:49:48.260 --> 00:49:49.320
for the girl.

00:49:49.320 --> 00:49:52.040
And I think that just
stems from my own can-do--

00:49:52.040 --> 00:49:53.810
I come from a very
immigrant family,

00:49:53.810 --> 00:49:56.630
like, you can do it, just
bootstrap it, figure it

00:49:56.630 --> 00:49:59.600
out kind of mentality
that I grew up with that

00:49:59.600 --> 00:50:01.645
actually wasn't fair to girls.

00:50:01.645 --> 00:50:03.020
The thing that
I've realized now,

00:50:03.020 --> 00:50:08.330
almost 10 years later, is that
the data that we see around

00:50:08.330 --> 00:50:11.840
the world, really, in terms
of what girls are facing

00:50:11.840 --> 00:50:14.240
around anxiety and
depression and stress,

00:50:14.240 --> 00:50:15.920
and the percentage
of girls who say

00:50:15.920 --> 00:50:18.290
on college campuses
at the age of 18

00:50:18.290 --> 00:50:21.060
that I feel overwhelmed
by all I have to do.

00:50:21.060 --> 00:50:23.210
These are all
stratospherically rising.

00:50:23.210 --> 00:50:25.310
That's not about
the girl's failure.

00:50:25.310 --> 00:50:28.660
That's about the way
we are failing girls.

00:50:28.660 --> 00:50:32.240
And I do think becoming a
parent changed things for me.

00:50:32.240 --> 00:50:35.120
It allowed me to see the
things that I could control

00:50:35.120 --> 00:50:37.326
and the things that I
can't, and that we all need

00:50:37.326 --> 00:50:38.450
to work together to change.

00:50:41.020 --> 00:50:42.770
TRUDI MCCANNA: All
right, another question

00:50:42.770 --> 00:50:44.045
from the Dory from Shralika.

00:50:44.045 --> 00:50:46.940
I apologize if I
butchered your name.

00:50:46.940 --> 00:50:49.880
She asks, teaching kids to
be independent versus being

00:50:49.880 --> 00:50:51.500
there through the process.

00:50:51.500 --> 00:50:55.610
Example-- would you sit with
them passively or actively

00:50:55.610 --> 00:50:58.370
through a homework, or
leave them to work it out

00:50:58.370 --> 00:51:00.380
and let them ask if
they have a question?

00:51:00.380 --> 00:51:01.963
RACHEL SIMMONS: Such
a great question.

00:51:01.963 --> 00:51:03.680
And I think as our
kids get older,

00:51:03.680 --> 00:51:05.810
that is the
million-dollar question,

00:51:05.810 --> 00:51:10.130
is where is the balance between
finding that zone of struggle

00:51:10.130 --> 00:51:12.620
and growth that doesn't
push them over the edge

00:51:12.620 --> 00:51:16.250
and make them deteriorate
into a tantrum or whatever.

00:51:16.250 --> 00:51:17.210
I think that is an art.

00:51:17.210 --> 00:51:19.070
It's not a science.

00:51:19.070 --> 00:51:21.169
I think that what
we want-- let me

00:51:21.169 --> 00:51:22.460
tell you what we want to avoid.

00:51:22.460 --> 00:51:24.380
We want to avoid
parenting and teaching

00:51:24.380 --> 00:51:27.560
girls who feel like they have
to ask every five minutes,

00:51:27.560 --> 00:51:28.267
is this right?

00:51:28.267 --> 00:51:28.850
Is this right?

00:51:28.850 --> 00:51:29.660
Did I get it right?

00:51:29.660 --> 00:51:31.220
I don't know if this is right.

00:51:31.220 --> 00:51:33.530
What happens is they
go to their teachers,

00:51:33.530 --> 00:51:36.200
and every couple of
minutes they keep asking,

00:51:36.200 --> 00:51:37.820
is this exactly what you want?

00:51:37.820 --> 00:51:39.710
Teachers are now
complaining about this to me

00:51:39.710 --> 00:51:41.090
all over the country.

00:51:41.090 --> 00:51:43.700
It's called learned
helplessness, basically.

00:51:43.700 --> 00:51:45.500
So it is support seeking, right?

00:51:45.500 --> 00:51:48.260
It looks like support
seeking, but really what it is

00:51:48.260 --> 00:51:51.110
is a fear that if I don't
get it exactly right,

00:51:51.110 --> 00:51:53.400
oh my god, it's
going to be a crisis.

00:51:53.400 --> 00:51:56.090
Now, that is not a muscle we
want our kids to cultivate.

00:51:56.090 --> 00:51:58.820
And if you hear your daughter's
teacher talk about this,

00:51:58.820 --> 00:52:00.067
it's really important.

00:52:00.067 --> 00:52:01.400
So how do you find that balance?

00:52:01.400 --> 00:52:03.358
Well, first of all, I
think you have to prepare

00:52:03.358 --> 00:52:04.820
your daughter beforehand.

00:52:04.820 --> 00:52:06.590
And you say, listen,
I know that you're

00:52:06.590 --> 00:52:07.730
going to be doing
your homework, and I

00:52:07.730 --> 00:52:09.070
want you to know that I'm here.

00:52:09.070 --> 00:52:11.060
And I also watch and
know that my goal is

00:52:11.060 --> 00:52:12.700
for you to challenge yourself.

00:52:12.700 --> 00:52:14.810
And so I might not be
as available to you

00:52:14.810 --> 00:52:16.670
as I usually am,
because I'm going to ask

00:52:16.670 --> 00:52:18.292
you to grapple with some stuff.

00:52:18.292 --> 00:52:20.000
Grapple might be a
big word for your kid,

00:52:20.000 --> 00:52:22.287
but I'm going to ask you
to work on stuff yourself.

00:52:22.287 --> 00:52:24.620
And I'm going to ask you to
come up with some strategies

00:52:24.620 --> 00:52:27.350
yourself for how you
could help yourself

00:52:27.350 --> 00:52:29.060
without necessarily using me.

00:52:29.060 --> 00:52:32.060
So I would say to a kid, what's
one thing you could do other

00:52:32.060 --> 00:52:33.260
than asking me?

00:52:33.260 --> 00:52:34.920
Maybe it's to call a friend.

00:52:34.920 --> 00:52:37.820
Those are all powerful
things that they can come up

00:52:37.820 --> 00:52:41.630
with to advocate for themselves,
to make good on a problem

00:52:41.630 --> 00:52:44.350
that they have, that don't
involve going to you.

00:52:44.350 --> 00:52:48.107
Then I think you have to
find that growth edge, right?

00:52:48.107 --> 00:52:49.190
I think that's the phrase.

00:52:49.190 --> 00:52:51.710
You have to find that
place with her where she's

00:52:51.710 --> 00:52:54.020
pushing herself
but not becoming so

00:52:54.020 --> 00:52:56.879
turned off by what she's doing
that she doesn't want to do it.

00:52:56.879 --> 00:52:57.920
Because here's the thing.

00:52:57.920 --> 00:53:00.960
I think when kids really start
to hate what they're doing,

00:53:00.960 --> 00:53:02.580
I mean, they hate
what they're doing.

00:53:02.580 --> 00:53:04.454
So we also have to make
sure that they're not

00:53:04.454 --> 00:53:06.930
getting undone.

00:53:06.930 --> 00:53:08.180
And like I said, it is an art.

00:53:08.180 --> 00:53:10.910
I wish I had a good hard
and fast rule for that.

00:53:10.910 --> 00:53:12.830
Actually, wait, I have
one more thing to say.

00:53:12.830 --> 00:53:14.320
Sorry, I did think of it.

00:53:14.320 --> 00:53:15.620
It's hard to think on
your feet, because I'm

00:53:15.620 --> 00:53:16.869
like, what would I really say?

00:53:16.869 --> 00:53:17.840
So here's what I think.

00:53:17.840 --> 00:53:20.090
I would actually
say to the kid, what

00:53:20.090 --> 00:53:22.040
is one way that you
could challenge yourself

00:53:22.040 --> 00:53:23.240
that you've never
challenged yourself

00:53:23.240 --> 00:53:24.490
before in doing your homework?

00:53:24.490 --> 00:53:26.270
That's what I would say.

00:53:26.270 --> 00:53:27.939
Let's come up with
something that you

00:53:27.939 --> 00:53:30.230
would do to push yourself
that you haven't done before.

00:53:30.230 --> 00:53:31.690
OK.

00:53:31.690 --> 00:53:32.840
TRUDI MCCANNA: All right, and
we've got one more question

00:53:32.840 --> 00:53:33.429
on the Dory.

00:53:33.429 --> 00:53:35.720
And I think it's the last
question we'll have time for.

00:53:35.720 --> 00:53:37.310
And it's, again, from Hillary.

00:53:37.310 --> 00:53:40.310
And she asks, what is your
take on single-gender education

00:53:40.310 --> 00:53:41.270
for girls?

00:53:41.270 --> 00:53:43.730
Are there specific situations,
personalities where

00:53:43.730 --> 00:53:45.210
parents should consider it?

00:53:45.210 --> 00:53:46.580
RACHEL SIMMONS: Yes, I think so.

00:53:46.580 --> 00:53:48.800
My take on single-gender
education for girls

00:53:48.800 --> 00:53:53.510
is that it can be
a very important

00:53:53.510 --> 00:53:57.540
and empowering and enriching
experience for certain girls,

00:53:57.540 --> 00:53:59.480
but not necessarily
for all girls.

00:53:59.480 --> 00:54:02.550
There's a lot of great
research out there about--

00:54:02.550 --> 00:54:06.230
for example, I'm thinking
of the work of Linda Sax

00:54:06.230 --> 00:54:08.660
at UCLA, who has looked
at the difference

00:54:08.660 --> 00:54:11.480
in self-reported
confidence levels

00:54:11.480 --> 00:54:14.270
in the first year of college
of girls who have attended

00:54:14.270 --> 00:54:16.557
coed schools versus
single gender schools,

00:54:16.557 --> 00:54:18.140
and there is a
significant difference.

00:54:18.140 --> 00:54:21.350
That the girls who come
from the all-girls school

00:54:21.350 --> 00:54:23.000
report higher levels
of confidence,

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:24.890
more speaking up in class.

00:54:24.890 --> 00:54:28.790
That being said, I think there
are wonderful benefits to being

00:54:28.790 --> 00:54:30.972
part of a coed community.

00:54:30.972 --> 00:54:32.930
I also think-- are there
certain kinds of girls

00:54:32.930 --> 00:54:35.221
that I would recommend
a single-sex school to?

00:54:35.221 --> 00:54:35.720
Yeah.

00:54:35.720 --> 00:54:37.340
I mean, I think
about this a lot for

00:54:37.340 --> 00:54:38.780
my own soon-to-be six-year-old.

00:54:38.780 --> 00:54:40.580
And I think that
if she turns out

00:54:40.580 --> 00:54:44.220
to be a kid who is very
vulnerable to social pressure,

00:54:44.220 --> 00:54:47.450
particularly around
boys, who has a hard time

00:54:47.450 --> 00:54:50.720
distinguishing between
what her own values are

00:54:50.720 --> 00:54:52.700
and what the values
of her peers are,

00:54:52.700 --> 00:54:54.500
I might seriously
consider putting her

00:54:54.500 --> 00:54:55.910
in an all-girls school.

00:54:55.910 --> 00:54:57.920
Because I do think
that particularly

00:54:57.920 --> 00:55:01.310
around middle school because I
think that during that period,

00:55:01.310 --> 00:55:03.830
the powerful,
intense expectations

00:55:03.830 --> 00:55:06.560
to conform to what
other people are doing

00:55:06.560 --> 00:55:09.230
can be very destructive
for certain kinds

00:55:09.230 --> 00:55:10.442
of kids who are vulnerable.

00:55:10.442 --> 00:55:12.650
So I'm thinking a lot about
that for my own daughter,

00:55:12.650 --> 00:55:14.600
and watching her.

00:55:14.600 --> 00:55:16.850
I also think that
for those girls who

00:55:16.850 --> 00:55:19.880
need more attention around
things like leadership

00:55:19.880 --> 00:55:22.070
development, speaking
up, girls schools

00:55:22.070 --> 00:55:24.860
tend to be more
oriented to focusing

00:55:24.860 --> 00:55:27.030
on what the vulnerabilities
are that girls bring.

00:55:27.030 --> 00:55:30.170
So I would say those two
points of vulnerability, to me,

00:55:30.170 --> 00:55:32.030
would be reason to
seriously consider

00:55:32.030 --> 00:55:33.311
an all-girls environment.

00:55:33.311 --> 00:55:34.310
TRUDI MCCANNA: Terrific.

00:55:34.310 --> 00:55:35.876
Well, with that,
we're out of time.

00:55:35.876 --> 00:55:37.250
Thank you so much
for joining us.

00:55:37.250 --> 00:55:37.440
RACHEL SIMMONS: Thank you.

00:55:37.440 --> 00:55:39.110
TRUDI MCCANNA: Join me in
thanking Rachel and Simone,

00:55:39.110 --> 00:55:39.610
please.

00:55:39.610 --> 00:55:41.120
